[49m[38;5;10m+      1[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # Recipe 6.8: Disease Subtype Discovery
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      2[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      3[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Complexity:** Complex · **Phase:** Research/Clinical · **Estimated Cost:** Variable (compute-heavy)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      4[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      5[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      6[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      7[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## The Problem
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      8[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      9[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Here's a dirty secret in medicine: many diseases we treat as single entities are actually collections of distinct conditions wearing the same name. "Type 2 diabetes" is not one disease. It's a label we slap on a heterogeneous group of metabolic dysfunctions that happen to share a common symptom (elevated blood glucose) but may have wildly different underlying mechanisms, progression patterns, and optimal treatments.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     10[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     11[0m:[38;5;10m[49m This isn't a theoretical concern. A patient with insulin-resistant Type 2 diabetes driven by visceral adiposity responds differently to metformin than a patient whose diabetes is primarily driven by beta-cell dysfunction. They both get the same ICD-10 code. They both get the same first-line treatment protocol. One of them responds well. The other doesn't, and we call that "treatment failure" when really it's "wrong treatment for this particular flavor of the disease."
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     12[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     13[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The same story plays out across oncology (breast cancer has at least four molecular subtypes with different prognoses), psychiatry (major depressive disorder is almost certainly multiple distinct conditions), autoimmune diseases (lupus presents so differently across patients that clinicians joke it's a dozen diseases), and cardiology (heart failure with preserved ejection fraction is a grab-bag of distinct pathophysiologies).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     14[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     15[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The clinical impact is enormous. If you can identify meaningful subtypes within a disease population, you can:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     16[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     17[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - Match patients to treatments that actually work for their specific subtype
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     18[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - Set realistic prognosis expectations (some subtypes progress faster)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     19[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - Design clinical trials that aren't diluted by heterogeneity (a drug that works for subtype A but not subtype B will fail a trial that mixes them)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     20[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - Identify biomarkers that distinguish subtypes early, before treatment failure reveals them
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     21[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     22[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The challenge: these subtypes aren't labeled in your data. Nobody tagged patients as "Type 2 diabetes subtype 3." You have to discover the structure from the data itself. That's unsupervised learning, and it's one of the hardest problems in clinical informatics because there's no answer key to check your work against.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     23[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     24[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     25[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     26[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## The Technology: Unsupervised Clustering for Subtype Discovery
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     27[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     28[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### What Is Unsupervised Clustering?
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     29[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     30[0m:[38;5;10m[49m At its core, unsupervised clustering is the process of finding natural groupings in data without being told what the groups are. You hand the algorithm a bunch of patient records described by dozens or hundreds of features (lab values, vital signs, genetic markers, medication responses, comorbidities) and ask: "Are there distinct subgroups here that look meaningfully different from each other?"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     31[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     32[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The algorithm doesn't know what a "disease subtype" is. It doesn't know what diabetes is. It just finds regions of the feature space where patients cluster together, separated from other clusters by measurable gaps. Your job is to look at what the algorithm found and determine whether those clusters correspond to something clinically real.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     33[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     34[0m:[38;5;10m[49m This is fundamentally different from supervised learning (where you have labeled examples to learn from) and from rule-based stratification (where a clinician defines the tiers). Unsupervised discovery can find structure that humans haven't noticed yet. That's its power and its danger.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     35[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     36[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### The Clustering Algorithm Landscape
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     37[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     38[0m:[38;5;10m[49m There's no single "best" clustering algorithm for disease subtype discovery. The right choice depends on your data characteristics and assumptions about cluster shape.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     39[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     40[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **K-Means and variants.** The workhorse. Partitions patients into K groups by minimizing within-cluster variance. Fast, scalable, interpretable. The catch: you have to specify K in advance (how many subtypes?), and it assumes roughly spherical clusters of similar size. For high-dimensional clinical data, those assumptions often don't hold. K-Means++ improves initialization; Mini-Batch K-Means handles large datasets.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     41[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     42[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Gaussian Mixture Models (GMM).** A probabilistic generalization of K-Means. Instead of hard cluster assignments, each patient gets a probability of belonging to each cluster. This is valuable in medicine because patients often don't fit neatly into one subtype. A patient might be 70% subtype A and 30% subtype B. GMMs also handle elliptical (non-spherical) cluster shapes. The downside: more parameters to estimate, more sensitive to initialization, and model selection (choosing K) requires information criteria like BIC or AIC.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     43[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     44[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Hierarchical clustering.** Builds a tree (dendrogram) of nested clusters, from individual patients up to the entire population. You can cut the tree at different levels to get different numbers of clusters. Useful for exploring structure at multiple granularities. Agglomerative (bottom-up) is more common than divisive (top-down). The downside: doesn't scale well beyond a few thousand patients without approximations, and the choice of linkage criterion (single, complete, Ward's) dramatically affects results.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     45[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     46[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **DBSCAN and density-based methods.** Finds clusters as dense regions separated by sparse regions. Doesn't require specifying K. Can find arbitrarily shaped clusters. Handles noise (patients that don't belong to any cluster). The downside: sensitive to the density threshold parameter (epsilon), and struggles with clusters of varying density, which is common in clinical data where some subtypes are rare.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     47[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     48[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Spectral clustering.** Constructs a similarity graph between patients and partitions it using eigenvectors of the graph Laplacian. Can find non-convex cluster shapes that K-Means misses. Useful when the "similarity" between patients is better captured by a custom kernel than by Euclidean distance. The downside: computationally expensive for large populations, and the number of clusters still needs to be specified.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     49[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     50[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Deep clustering (autoencoders + clustering).** Uses a neural network to learn a low-dimensional representation of patients, then clusters in that learned space. Can capture complex nonlinear relationships between features. Increasingly popular in genomics and multi-omics subtyping. The downside: less interpretable (what do the learned dimensions mean?), requires more data, and adds hyperparameter complexity.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     51[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     52[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Why This Is Hard
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     53[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     54[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Disease subtype discovery is not a standard clustering problem. Several factors make it uniquely challenging:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     55[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     56[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **No ground truth.** In a typical ML problem, you can evaluate your model against known correct answers. Here, the whole point is that the correct answers don't exist yet. You're proposing new categories. Validation requires clinical interpretation, external cohort replication, and ideally prospective studies showing that the subtypes predict different outcomes or treatment responses.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     57[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     58[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Feature selection is everything.** Which patient attributes do you cluster on? Lab values? Genetic markers? Medication history? Comorbidities? Vital sign trajectories? The choice of features determines what kind of subtypes you'll find. Cluster on metabolic markers and you'll find metabolic subtypes. Cluster on genetic variants and you'll find genetic subtypes. These may or may not align. There's no objectively correct feature set; it depends on what clinical question you're trying to answer.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     59[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     60[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Dimensionality.** Clinical datasets often have hundreds of features per patient. High-dimensional spaces are treacherous for clustering: distances become less meaningful (the "curse of dimensionality"), noise features dilute signal features, and visualization becomes impossible. Dimensionality reduction (PCA, UMAP, t-SNE, autoencoders) is almost always necessary, but each method makes different assumptions about what structure to preserve.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     61[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     62[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Missing data.** Clinical data is notoriously incomplete. Not every patient has every lab test. Missingness is often informative (a test wasn't ordered because the clinician didn't suspect a condition). Simple imputation can introduce bias. Multiple imputation adds complexity. Some clustering methods handle missing data natively; most don't.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     63[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     64[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Temporal complexity.** Diseases evolve over time. A patient's subtype might change as their condition progresses. Cross-sectional clustering (one snapshot per patient) misses this. Longitudinal clustering (trajectories over time) is more informative but dramatically more complex.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     65[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     66[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Clinical meaningfulness.** Finding clusters is easy. Finding clusters that matter is hard. A clustering algorithm will always find groups if you ask it to. The question is whether those groups correspond to distinct biological mechanisms, different prognoses, or different treatment responses. Statistical separation is necessary but not sufficient for clinical relevance.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     67[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     68[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Where the Field Has Moved
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     69[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     70[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The last five years have seen significant advances:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     71[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     72[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Multi-omics integration.** Combining genomics, transcriptomics, proteomics, and metabolomics data for subtyping. Methods like MOFA (Multi-Omics Factor Analysis) and similarity network fusion handle heterogeneous data types.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     73[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     74[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Consensus clustering.** Running multiple clustering algorithms (or the same algorithm with different parameters) and identifying stable clusters that appear consistently. Reduces sensitivity to algorithmic choices.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     75[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     76[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Deep phenotyping from EHR data.** Using the full richness of electronic health records (not just structured fields but also clinical notes via NLP) to build patient representations for clustering.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     77[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     78[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Causal subtyping.** Moving beyond correlational clusters to identify subtypes with distinct causal mechanisms, often integrating Mendelian randomization or instrumental variable approaches.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     79[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     80[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Federated subtype discovery.** Running clustering across multiple institutions without sharing patient-level data, enabling larger effective sample sizes while preserving privacy.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     81[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     82[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     83[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     84[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## General Architecture Pattern
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     85[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     86[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The pipeline for disease subtype discovery follows a research-oriented workflow that's more iterative than a typical production ML pipeline:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     87[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     88[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     89[0m:[38;5;10m[49m [Cohort Definition] → [Feature Engineering] → [Dimensionality Reduction] →
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     90[0m:[38;5;10m[49m [Clustering] → [Cluster Validation] → [Clinical Interpretation] →
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     91[0m:[38;5;10m[49m [External Replication] → [Subtype Characterization]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     92[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     93[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     94[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Cohort Definition.** Select the patient population. This sounds simple but involves critical decisions: which diagnosis codes define the disease? What's the minimum observation window? How do you handle patients with multiple qualifying conditions? Inclusion/exclusion criteria directly affect what subtypes you can discover.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     95[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     96[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Feature Engineering.** Transform raw clinical data into a patient-feature matrix. Aggregate longitudinal data into summary statistics (mean HbA1c over 2 years, rate of eGFR decline, number of hospitalizations). Handle categorical variables (medications, comorbidities) via encoding. Normalize continuous features to prevent scale-dominant clustering.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     97[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     98[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Dimensionality Reduction.** Reduce the feature space to a manageable number of dimensions while preserving meaningful structure. PCA for linear relationships, UMAP or t-SNE for nonlinear manifold structure, autoencoders for complex learned representations. The reduced space is where clustering happens.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     99[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    100[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Clustering.** Apply one or more clustering algorithms to the reduced feature space. Run multiple algorithms and multiple parameter settings. Use ensemble/consensus approaches to identify robust clusters.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    101[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    102[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Cluster Validation.** Assess cluster quality using internal metrics (silhouette score, Calinski-Harabasz index, Davies-Bouldin index) and stability metrics (bootstrap resampling, cross-validation). Determine the optimal number of clusters using elbow methods, gap statistics, or information criteria.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    103[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    104[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Clinical Interpretation.** The most important step. Characterize each cluster by its distinguishing features. Are the clusters clinically coherent? Do they map to known biology? Do they predict different outcomes? This requires domain expertise and often iterative refinement.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    105[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    106[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **External Replication.** Validate discovered subtypes in an independent cohort. If the same clusters appear in a different population, they're more likely to reflect real biology rather than dataset-specific artifacts.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    107[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    108[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Subtype Characterization.** For validated subtypes, build a complete clinical profile: demographics, biomarkers, comorbidity patterns, treatment responses, prognosis. Develop a classifier that can assign new patients to subtypes for prospective use.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    109[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    110[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    111[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    112[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## The AWS Implementation
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    113[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    114[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Why These Services
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    115[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    116[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Amazon SageMaker for the ML pipeline.** Subtype discovery is an iterative, compute-intensive research workflow. SageMaker provides managed Jupyter notebooks for exploration, built-in clustering algorithms (K-Means), support for custom algorithms via containers, distributed training for large cohorts, and experiment tracking via SageMaker Experiments. The notebook environment is where researchers spend most of their time, and SageMaker handles the infrastructure so they can focus on the science.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    117[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    118[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Amazon S3 for data lake storage.** Clinical datasets for subtyping are large (thousands of patients, hundreds of features, often with longitudinal data) and come in multiple formats (Parquet for structured data, CSV exports from EHRs, FHIR bundles). S3 provides durable, encrypted storage with lifecycle policies for managing research data retention.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    119[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    120[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **AWS Glue for ETL and feature engineering.** Transforming raw EHR extracts into a clean patient-feature matrix requires significant data wrangling: joining tables, aggregating longitudinal records, encoding categoricals, handling missing values. Glue's serverless Spark environment handles this at scale without cluster management.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    121[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    122[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Amazon Athena for cohort definition.** Defining the study cohort (which patients meet inclusion criteria) is a SQL problem. Athena lets researchers query the data lake directly with standard SQL, iterate on cohort definitions quickly, and export results to S3 for downstream processing.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    123[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    124[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Amazon SageMaker Processing for batch computation.** Dimensionality reduction and consensus clustering are compute-intensive batch jobs. SageMaker Processing provides managed compute instances that spin up, run the job, and shut down. No idle infrastructure costs between experiments.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    125[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    126[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Amazon QuickSight for visualization.** Communicating subtype characteristics to clinical stakeholders requires clear visualizations: cluster plots, feature distributions by subtype, outcome curves. QuickSight connects directly to S3/Athena results for interactive dashboards.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    127[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    128[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Architecture Diagram
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    129[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    130[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```mermaid
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    131[0m:[38;5;10m[49m flowchart TD
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    132[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     A[EHR Data Extract] -->|Raw clinical data| B[S3 Data Lake\nraw/]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    133[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     B -->|ETL| C[AWS Glue\nFeature Engineering]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    134[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     C -->|Patient-feature matrix| D[S3 Data Lake\nprocessed/]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    135[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    136[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     E[Amazon Athena] -->|Cohort SQL| D
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    137[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    138[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     D -->|Training data| F[SageMaker Notebook\nExploration & Prototyping]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    139[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     D -->|Batch input| G[SageMaker Processing\nDimensionality Reduction]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    140[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     G -->|Reduced features| H[SageMaker Training\nClustering Algorithms]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    141[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     H -->|Cluster assignments| I[S3 Data Lake\nresults/]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    142[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    143[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     I -->|Validation metrics| J[SageMaker Experiments\nTracking & Comparison]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    144[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     I -->|Visualization| K[Amazon QuickSight\nSubtype Dashboards]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    145[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    146[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     F -.->|Interactive iteration| G
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    147[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     F -.->|Interactive iteration| H
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    148[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    149[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     style B fill:#f9f,stroke:#333
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    150[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     style D fill:#f9f,stroke:#333
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    151[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     style I fill:#f9f,stroke:#333
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    152[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     style H fill:#ff9,stroke:#333
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    153[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     style K fill:#9ff,stroke:#333
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    154[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    155[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    156[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Prerequisites
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    157[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    158[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | Requirement | Details |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    159[0m:[38;5;10m[49m |-------------|---------|
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    160[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **AWS Services** | Amazon SageMaker, Amazon S3, AWS Glue, Amazon Athena, Amazon QuickSight |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    161[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **IAM Permissions** | `sagemaker:*` (scoped to project), `s3:GetObject`, `s3:PutObject`, `glue:StartJobRun`, `athena:StartQueryExecution` |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    162[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **BAA** | AWS BAA signed (patient clinical data is PHI) |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    163[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Encryption** | S3: SSE-KMS; SageMaker notebooks: EBS encryption; Glue: job bookmarks encrypted; all transit over TLS |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    164[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **VPC** | SageMaker notebooks and processing jobs in private subnets with VPC endpoints for S3, SageMaker API, and CloudWatch Logs |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    165[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **CloudTrail** | Enabled: log all data access for HIPAA audit trail |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    166[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Sample Data** | De-identified research datasets (MIMIC-IV for ICU populations, UK Biobank for chronic disease). Never use identifiable patient data without IRB approval. |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    167[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Cost Estimate** | Highly variable. Typical research project: $200-500/month (SageMaker notebooks + periodic processing jobs). Large-scale runs with GPU instances: $50-200 per experiment. |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    168[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    169[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Ingredients
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    170[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    171[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | AWS Service | Role |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    172[0m:[38;5;10m[49m |------------|------|
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    173[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Amazon SageMaker** | ML experimentation, training, processing jobs |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    174[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Amazon S3** | Data lake for raw, processed, and result datasets |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    175[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **AWS Glue** | ETL pipeline for feature engineering at scale |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    176[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Amazon Athena** | SQL-based cohort definition and ad-hoc queries |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    177[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Amazon QuickSight** | Visualization dashboards for clinical stakeholders |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    178[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **AWS KMS** | Encryption key management for all data at rest |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    179[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Amazon CloudWatch** | Monitoring for long-running processing jobs |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    180[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **SageMaker Experiments** | Tracking clustering runs, parameters, and metrics |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    181[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    182[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Code
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    183[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    184[0m:[38;5;10m[49m #### Walkthrough
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    185[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    186[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Step 1: Cohort definition.** Before any ML happens, you need to precisely define which patients are in your study population. This is a clinical decision with technical implementation. For diabetes subtyping, you might require: confirmed Type 2 diabetes diagnosis (ICD-10 E11.x), at least 2 years of continuous enrollment, age 30+ at diagnosis (to exclude likely Type 1 misclassifications), and no secondary diabetes causes. The cohort definition directly determines what subtypes you can discover. Too broad and you'll find subtypes that are really just different diseases mixed together. Too narrow and you'll miss rare but real subtypes. This step uses SQL against your clinical data warehouse.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    187[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    188[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    189[0m:[38;5;10m[49m FUNCTION define_cohort(data_lake_path):
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    190[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Query the clinical data lake to identify eligible patients.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    191[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Each criterion is a deliberate clinical decision, not arbitrary filtering.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    192[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    193[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     query = """
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    194[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         SELECT DISTINCT patient_id
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    195[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         FROM diagnoses
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    196[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         WHERE icd10_code LIKE 'E11%'           -- Type 2 diabetes diagnosis
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    197[0m:[38;5;10m[49m           AND diagnosis_date >= '2020-01-01'    -- Recent enough for complete data
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    198[0m:[38;5;10m[49m           AND patient_age_at_diagnosis >= 30    -- Exclude likely Type 1 misclassifications
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    199[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    200[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         INTERSECT
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    201[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    202[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         SELECT patient_id
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    203[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         FROM enrollment
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    204[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         WHERE continuous_months >= 24           -- Enough observation time for meaningful features
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    205[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    206[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         EXCEPT
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    207[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    208[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         SELECT patient_id
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    209[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         FROM diagnoses
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    210[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         WHERE icd10_code IN ('E08%', 'E09%')   -- Exclude drug-induced and post-procedural diabetes
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    211[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     """
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    212[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    213[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Execute against the data lake and save the cohort list
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    214[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     cohort_ids = execute_query(query, output_path=data_lake_path + "/cohort/")
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    215[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    216[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     RETURN cohort_ids
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    217[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Typical result: 15,000-50,000 patients depending on your health system size
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    218[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    219[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    220[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Step 2: Feature engineering.** This is where clinical knowledge meets data engineering. You're transforming raw longitudinal records (thousands of lab results, vital signs, medication fills per patient) into a fixed-width feature vector that captures each patient's disease phenotype. The feature choices encode your hypothesis about what distinguishes subtypes. For metabolic subtyping, you might focus on: glycemic control trajectory, insulin resistance markers, beta-cell function indicators, lipid profiles, body composition, and comorbidity burden. Each feature needs careful aggregation (mean? trend? variability?) and normalization.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    221[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    222[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    223[0m:[38;5;10m[49m FUNCTION engineer_features(cohort_ids, data_lake_path):
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    224[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // For each patient in the cohort, compute a comprehensive feature vector.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    225[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // These features encode our hypothesis about what distinguishes subtypes.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    226[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    227[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     features = empty matrix (rows = patients, columns = features)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    228[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    229[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     FOR each patient_id in cohort_ids:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    230[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // Glycemic control features
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    231[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         hba1c_values = get_lab_results(patient_id, test="HbA1c", window="2 years")
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    232[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         features[patient_id]["hba1c_mean"]      = mean(hba1c_values)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    233[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         features[patient_id]["hba1c_trend"]      = linear_slope(hba1c_values)  // improving or worsening?
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    234[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         features[patient_id]["hba1c_variability"] = coefficient_of_variation(hba1c_values)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    235[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    236[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // Insulin resistance markers
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    237[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         features[patient_id]["fasting_glucose_mean"] = mean(get_labs(patient_id, "fasting_glucose"))
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    238[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         features[patient_id]["triglyceride_mean"]    = mean(get_labs(patient_id, "triglycerides"))
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    239[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         features[patient_id]["homa_ir"]              = compute_homa_ir(patient_id)  // if insulin levels available
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    240[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    241[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // Beta-cell function indicators
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    242[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         features[patient_id]["c_peptide"]         = latest(get_labs(patient_id, "c_peptide"))
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    243[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         features[patient_id]["time_to_insulin"]   = months_from_diagnosis_to_first_insulin(patient_id)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    244[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    245[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // Body composition
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    246[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         features[patient_id]["bmi_mean"]          = mean(get_vitals(patient_id, "bmi"))
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    247[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         features[patient_id]["bmi_trend"]         = linear_slope(get_vitals(patient_id, "bmi"))
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    248[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    249[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // Comorbidity burden
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    250[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         features[patient_id]["n_comorbidities"]   = count_unique_chronic_conditions(patient_id)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    251[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         features[patient_id]["has_cvd"]           = has_diagnosis(patient_id, cardiovascular_codes)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    252[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         features[patient_id]["has_ckd"]           = has_diagnosis(patient_id, renal_codes)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    253[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         features[patient_id]["has_neuropathy"]    = has_diagnosis(patient_id, neuropathy_codes)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    254[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    255[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // Treatment response (outcome-adjacent, use carefully)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    256[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         features[patient_id]["metformin_response"] = hba1c_change_after_medication(patient_id, "metformin")
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    257[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         features[patient_id]["n_medication_classes"] = count_diabetes_med_classes(patient_id)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    258[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    259[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Handle missing values: multiple imputation for features missing < 30%,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    260[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // drop features missing > 50% of values (too sparse to be informative)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    261[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     features = handle_missing_data(features, strategy="multiple_imputation", threshold=0.5)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    262[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    263[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Normalize all continuous features to zero mean, unit variance.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    264[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Without this, features on larger scales (glucose in mg/dL) dominate
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    265[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // features on smaller scales (HbA1c in %) during distance calculations.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    266[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     features = standardize(features, method="z_score")
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    267[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    268[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Save the patient-feature matrix
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    269[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     save_to_parquet(features, data_lake_path + "/features/patient_feature_matrix.parquet")
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    270[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    271[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     RETURN features
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    272[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    273[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    274[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Step 3: Dimensionality reduction.** With 20-50 features per patient, direct clustering is feasible but noisy. Dimensionality reduction serves two purposes: it removes noise and redundancy (correlated features get collapsed), and it enables visualization (you can plot 2D or 3D projections to visually inspect cluster structure). PCA is the standard first pass because it's linear, deterministic, and interpretable (each component is a weighted combination of original features). UMAP provides better nonlinear structure preservation for visualization. Use both: PCA for the actual clustering input, UMAP for the plots you show clinicians.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    275[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    276[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    277[0m:[38;5;10m[49m FUNCTION reduce_dimensions(features):
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    278[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Step 3a: PCA for clustering input
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    279[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Retain enough components to explain 90% of variance.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    280[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // This typically reduces 30-50 features down to 8-15 components.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    281[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     pca_model = fit_PCA(features, variance_threshold=0.90)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    282[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     pca_features = pca_model.transform(features)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    283[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    284[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     n_components = pca_features.n_columns
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    285[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Log: "Retained {n_components} PCA components explaining 90% of variance"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    286[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    287[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Inspect component loadings to understand what each dimension captures.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    288[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Component 1 might be "overall metabolic severity"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    289[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Component 2 might be "insulin resistance vs. beta-cell failure axis"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    290[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     loadings = pca_model.get_loadings()
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    291[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     save_loadings_report(loadings, "results/pca_loadings.csv")
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    292[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    293[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Step 3b: UMAP for visualization (not for clustering input)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    294[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // UMAP preserves local neighborhood structure, making clusters visually apparent.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    295[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // n_neighbors controls local vs. global structure preservation.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    296[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     umap_2d = fit_UMAP(features, n_components=2, n_neighbors=30, min_dist=0.1)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    297[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     save_visualization(umap_2d, "results/umap_projection.png")
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    298[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    299[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     RETURN pca_features, umap_2d
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    300[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    301[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    302[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Step 4: Consensus clustering.** Rather than betting on a single algorithm with a single parameter setting, consensus clustering runs many configurations and identifies clusters that are stable across them. The intuition: if two patients consistently end up in the same cluster regardless of which algorithm you use or how you perturb the data, they probably genuinely belong together. This is critical for subtype discovery because you need to convince clinicians (and reviewers, and the FDA) that your subtypes are real, not artifacts of a particular algorithmic choice.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    303[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    304[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    305[0m:[38;5;10m[49m FUNCTION consensus_clustering(pca_features, k_range):
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    306[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Run multiple clustering approaches and find stable consensus.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    307[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // k_range is typically [2, 3, 4, 5, 6, 7, 8] — we don't know how many subtypes exist.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    308[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    309[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Co-association matrix: tracks how often each pair of patients clusters together
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    310[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // across all runs. Size = n_patients x n_patients. Values range 0 to 1.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    311[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     n_patients = pca_features.n_rows
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    312[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     co_association = zero_matrix(n_patients, n_patients)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    313[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     n_runs = 0
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    314[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    315[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     FOR each k in k_range:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    316[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // Run K-Means with multiple random initializations
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    317[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         FOR iteration in 1 to 50:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    318[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             // Subsample 80% of patients (bootstrap stability)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    319[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             subsample_idx = random_sample(n_patients, fraction=0.80)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    320[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             subsample_data = pca_features[subsample_idx]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    321[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    322[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             labels = fit_kmeans(subsample_data, k=k, random_seed=iteration)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    323[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    324[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             // Update co-association: patients in the same cluster get +1
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    325[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             FOR each pair (i, j) in subsample_idx:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    326[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 IF labels[i] == labels[j]:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    327[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                     co_association[i][j] += 1
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    328[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             n_runs += 1
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    329[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    330[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // Also run Gaussian Mixture Model for this k
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    331[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         FOR iteration in 1 to 20:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    332[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             subsample_idx = random_sample(n_patients, fraction=0.80)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    333[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             subsample_data = pca_features[subsample_idx]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    334[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    335[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             labels = fit_gmm(subsample_data, n_components=k, random_seed=iteration)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    336[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    337[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             FOR each pair (i, j) in subsample_idx:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    338[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 IF labels[i] == labels[j]:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    339[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                     co_association[i][j] += 1
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    340[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             n_runs += 1
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    341[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    342[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Normalize co-association matrix to [0, 1]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    343[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     co_association = co_association / n_runs
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    344[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    345[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Final clustering on the co-association matrix itself.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    346[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Hierarchical clustering with average linkage works well here.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    347[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // The co-association matrix IS the similarity measure.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    348[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     final_labels = hierarchical_cluster(co_association, method="average")
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    349[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    350[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     RETURN co_association, final_labels
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    351[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    352[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    353[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Step 5: Determine optimal cluster count.** How many subtypes exist? This is the million-dollar question, and there's no single correct answer. Multiple metrics provide different perspectives. The Silhouette score measures how well-separated clusters are. The Calinski-Harabasz index rewards compact, well-separated clusters. The gap statistic compares your clustering to a null (random) distribution. Consensus matrix heatmaps show whether the co-association matrix has clean block-diagonal structure. Ultimately, the "right" number of clusters is the one that's both statistically supported AND clinically interpretable.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    354[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    355[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    356[0m:[38;5;10m[49m FUNCTION determine_optimal_k(pca_features, co_association, k_range):
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    357[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Compute multiple metrics for each candidate k.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    358[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // No single metric is definitive; look for convergence across metrics.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    359[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    360[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     metrics = empty table (columns: k, silhouette, calinski_harabasz, gap_statistic, bic)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    361[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    362[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     FOR each k in k_range:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    363[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         labels = cut_dendrogram(co_association, k=k)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    364[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    365[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // Silhouette: ranges -1 to 1. Higher = better separated clusters.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    366[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // Values > 0.5 indicate reasonable structure. > 0.7 is strong.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    367[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         sil = silhouette_score(pca_features, labels)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    368[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    369[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // Calinski-Harabasz: ratio of between-cluster to within-cluster variance.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    370[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // Higher is better. Look for a peak or elbow.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    371[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         ch = calinski_harabasz_score(pca_features, labels)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    372[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    373[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // Gap statistic: compares clustering quality to random expectation.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    374[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // Choose smallest k where gap(k) >= gap(k+1) - standard_error(k+1)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    375[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         gap = gap_statistic(pca_features, labels, n_references=50)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    376[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    377[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // BIC from GMM fit: penalizes model complexity.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    378[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // Lower is better. Balances fit quality against number of parameters.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    379[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         gmm = fit_gmm(pca_features, n_components=k)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    380[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         bic = gmm.bic(pca_features)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    381[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    382[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         metrics.add_row(k, sil, ch, gap, bic)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    383[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    384[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Present all metrics to the research team. The final decision is clinical.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    385[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     save_metrics_report(metrics, "results/cluster_count_metrics.csv")
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    386[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     plot_metrics(metrics, "results/cluster_count_plots.png")
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    387[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    388[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Automated suggestion (can be overridden by clinical judgment):
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    389[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     optimal_k = k with highest silhouette score among those with gap statistic support
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    390[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    391[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     RETURN optimal_k, metrics
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    392[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    393[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    394[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Step 6: Cluster validation and characterization.** Once you've settled on a cluster count, you need to validate that the clusters are stable and characterize what makes each one distinct. Stability testing uses bootstrap resampling: if you perturb the data slightly, do the same clusters appear? Feature importance analysis identifies which clinical features most strongly distinguish each cluster. Outcome association tests whether clusters predict different clinical trajectories.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    395[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    396[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    397[0m:[38;5;10m[49m FUNCTION validate_and_characterize(features, labels, outcomes):
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    398[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Stability assessment: bootstrap the cohort and re-cluster.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    399[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Measure how consistently patients are assigned to the same cluster.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    400[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     stability_scores = empty list
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    401[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     FOR iteration in 1 to 100:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    402[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         bootstrap_idx = random_sample_with_replacement(n_patients)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    403[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         bootstrap_labels = recluster(features[bootstrap_idx])
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    404[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    405[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // Adjusted Rand Index: 1.0 = perfect agreement, 0 = random
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    406[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         ari = adjusted_rand_index(labels[bootstrap_idx], bootstrap_labels)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    407[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         stability_scores.append(ari)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    408[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    409[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     mean_stability = mean(stability_scores)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    410[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // ARI > 0.8 indicates strong stability. < 0.6 is concerning.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    411[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     log("Cluster stability (mean ARI): {mean_stability}")
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    412[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    413[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Feature importance: which features distinguish clusters?
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    414[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Use Kruskal-Wallis test (non-parametric ANOVA) for each feature across clusters.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    415[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     feature_importance = empty table
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    416[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     FOR each feature_name in features.columns:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    417[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         groups = [features[feature_name][labels == k] for k in unique(labels)]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    418[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         h_stat, p_value = kruskal_wallis_test(groups)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    419[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         effect_size = eta_squared(groups)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    420[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         feature_importance.add_row(feature_name, h_stat, p_value, effect_size)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    421[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    422[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Sort by effect size to identify the most discriminating features
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    423[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     feature_importance = sort_by(feature_importance, "effect_size", descending=True)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    424[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    425[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Outcome association: do clusters predict different trajectories?
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    426[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Test against clinically meaningful outcomes.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    427[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     outcome_tests = empty table
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    428[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     FOR each outcome in ["time_to_insulin", "hba1c_at_3_years", "cvd_event", "ckd_progression"]:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    429[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         IF outcome is continuous:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    430[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             stat, p = kruskal_wallis_test(outcomes[outcome] grouped by labels)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    431[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         ELSE:  // binary outcome
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    432[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             stat, p = chi_squared_test(outcomes[outcome] vs labels)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    433[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         outcome_tests.add_row(outcome, stat, p)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    434[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    435[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Generate cluster profiles: median values of top features per cluster
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    436[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     cluster_profiles = empty table
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    437[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     FOR each k in unique(labels):
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    438[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         cluster_patients = features[labels == k]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    439[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         profile = compute_medians_and_iqr(cluster_patients, top_features)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    440[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         cluster_profiles.add_row(k, count=len(cluster_patients), profile)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    441[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    442[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     RETURN {
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    443[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         stability: mean_stability,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    444[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         feature_importance: feature_importance,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    445[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         outcome_associations: outcome_tests,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    446[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         cluster_profiles: cluster_profiles
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    447[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     }
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    448[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    449[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    450[0m:[38;5;10m[49m > **Curious how this looks in Python?** The pseudocode above covers the concepts. If you'd like to see sample Python code that demonstrates these patterns using boto3 and scikit-learn, check out the [Python Example](chapter06.08-python-example). It walks through each step with inline comments and notes on what you'd need to change for a real deployment.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    451[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    452[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Expected Results
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    453[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    454[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Sample output for a Type 2 diabetes subtyping study (illustrative, not from a real study):**
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    455[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    456[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```json
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    457[0m:[38;5;10m[49m {
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    458[0m:[38;5;10m[49m   "study_id": "t2d-subtype-discovery-2026-03",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    459[0m:[38;5;10m[49m   "cohort_size": 23847,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    460[0m:[38;5;10m[49m   "optimal_k": 4,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    461[0m:[38;5;10m[49m   "cluster_stability_ari": 0.82,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    462[0m:[38;5;10m[49m   "subtypes": [
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    463[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     {
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    464[0m:[38;5;10m[49m       "cluster_id": 0,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    465[0m:[38;5;10m[49m       "n_patients": 8234,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    466[0m:[38;5;10m[49m       "label": "Insulin-Resistant Obesity-Driven",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    467[0m:[38;5;10m[49m       "distinguishing_features": ["high BMI", "high triglycerides", "high HOMA-IR", "preserved C-peptide"],
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    468[0m:[38;5;10m[49m       "median_hba1c": 7.8,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    469[0m:[38;5;10m[49m       "median_bmi": 34.2,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    470[0m:[38;5;10m[49m       "metformin_response": "good"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    471[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     },
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    472[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     {
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    473[0m:[38;5;10m[49m       "cluster_id": 1,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    474[0m:[38;5;10m[49m       "n_patients": 6102,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    475[0m:[38;5;10m[49m       "label": "Age-Related Beta-Cell Decline",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    476[0m:[38;5;10m[49m       "distinguishing_features": ["older age", "low C-peptide", "rapid HbA1c rise", "normal BMI"],
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    477[0m:[38;5;10m[49m       "median_hba1c": 8.4,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    478[0m:[38;5;10m[49m       "median_bmi": 26.1,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    479[0m:[38;5;10m[49m       "metformin_response": "poor"
